1
00:00:07,542 --> 00:00:10,917
[foreboding music playing]

2
00:00:15,333 --> 00:00:16,958
[indistinct clamor]

3
00:00:17,042 --> 00:00:17,917
[gun cocks]

4
00:00:18,000 --> 00:00:19,208
[echoing clamor]

5
00:00:19,292 --> 00:00:21,958
- [echoing gunfire]
- [distorted echoing scream]

6
00:00:22,042 --> 00:00:24,333
[echoing fades]

7
00:00:32,750 --> 00:00:35,417
[somber music playing]

8
00:00:44,583 --> 00:00:48,083
[indistinct chatter]

9
00:00:59,000 --> 00:01:00,958
That woman is not Seya's sister.

10
00:01:02,583 --> 00:01:05,375
She's a Thai woman
who was recently tricked onto the boat.

11
00:01:11,042 --> 00:01:13,458
[sobs]

12
00:01:20,250 --> 00:01:22,833
[sobbing]

13
00:01:28,083 --> 00:01:30,958
[music rises, darkens]

14
00:01:41,417 --> 00:01:45,500
THE EVIL LAWYER

15
00:01:45,625 --> 00:01:46,625
[music concludes]

16
00:01:46,708 --> 00:01:48,875
[chains jangling]

17
00:01:52,750 --> 00:01:54,458
[Chai] How are you holding up?

18
00:01:55,417 --> 00:01:57,375
I'll ask the wardens to look after you.

19
00:01:58,042 --> 00:02:00,000
Don't worry about a damn thing.

20
00:02:00,083 --> 00:02:01,125
[Leh] Okay.

21
00:02:02,625 --> 00:02:04,917
Let's go. Staying too long
could look suspicious.

22
00:02:11,958 --> 00:02:14,875
Don't forget my dad on the ship.
Please help him.

23
00:02:15,667 --> 00:02:18,042
[soft tense music playing]

24
00:02:31,125 --> 00:02:32,125
Get in the car.

25
00:03:07,542 --> 00:03:08,875
I need to take a piss.

26
00:03:10,208 --> 00:03:12,625
Tell me what happened when he vanished.

27
00:03:12,708 --> 00:03:13,917
[music falls]

28
00:03:19,292 --> 00:03:22,833
That day, I arrested him at the pier
by the Moei River.

29
00:03:23,542 --> 00:03:26,583
Our unit got a lead
that he was involved in human trafficking,

30
00:03:27,542 --> 00:03:29,625
so we did our duty and arrested him.

31
00:03:31,083 --> 00:03:32,542
Where did the lead come from?

32
00:03:33,875 --> 00:03:35,083
From an informant.

33
00:03:35,750 --> 00:03:37,417
Anan already had his eye on him.

34
00:03:38,250 --> 00:03:40,500
Your dad was smuggling Burmese migrants,

35
00:03:41,042 --> 00:03:42,792
so we raided the place.

36
00:03:43,833 --> 00:03:46,667
We took him to a safe house
in the woods near the Mekong.

37
00:03:47,667 --> 00:03:48,583
[sighs]

38
00:03:50,042 --> 00:03:52,667
That day, Anan went in to interrogate him.

39
00:03:55,000 --> 00:03:56,750
By the time Anan left the room…

40
00:03:58,750 --> 00:04:00,250
your dad was already dead.

41
00:04:00,333 --> 00:04:02,375
[music rises]

42
00:04:04,917 --> 00:04:08,375
[Chai] I was ordered to destroy
all the evidence and leave no trace.

43
00:04:10,208 --> 00:04:13,083
So I wrote in the report
that the suspect had escaped.

44
00:04:15,417 --> 00:04:17,250
Why didn't you say you were forced?!

45
00:04:18,292 --> 00:04:20,583
If I did, would I still be alive today?

46
00:04:21,333 --> 00:04:24,333
Everyone knows how damn powerful Anan is.

47
00:04:24,958 --> 00:04:27,458
Your dad was too stubborn.
If he had just paid up front--

48
00:04:27,542 --> 00:04:29,542
- [music falls]
- [tires screech]

49
00:04:29,625 --> 00:04:30,708
[handbrake creaks]

50
00:04:31,458 --> 00:04:32,333
[Chanon exhales]

51
00:04:32,917 --> 00:04:35,583
Didn't you need to piss? Go!

52
00:04:43,292 --> 00:04:44,458
[sighs]

53
00:04:44,542 --> 00:04:45,458
[seatbelt clicks]

54
00:04:46,583 --> 00:04:47,750
[Jittri sobs]

55
00:04:47,833 --> 00:04:50,500
[somber music playing]

56
00:04:57,500 --> 00:05:00,542
[sobbing]

57
00:05:21,750 --> 00:05:25,083
[music turns suspenseful]

58
00:05:26,667 --> 00:05:28,417
DARLING MAYSA

59
00:05:28,500 --> 00:05:29,417
[cell phone buzzing]

60
00:05:30,583 --> 00:05:31,667
[sighs]

61
00:05:31,750 --> 00:05:34,375
Hey, honey. I was just about to call you.

62
00:05:34,458 --> 00:05:37,958
<i>Where are you?</i>
<i>The cops just swarmed our house.</i>

63
00:05:38,042 --> 00:05:41,375
<i>They said they raided your boat</i>
<i>for illegal workers.</i>

64
00:05:42,083 --> 00:05:45,250
<i>They also said the captain</i>
<i>shot them all dead.</i>

65
00:05:45,333 --> 00:05:47,708
Hey, I had no idea.

66
00:05:48,250 --> 00:05:49,708
Who came to our house?

67
00:05:49,792 --> 00:05:51,875
Was it Eak and the guys from my birthday?

68
00:05:51,958 --> 00:05:56,042
<i>I've never seen them before.</i>
<i>They're all gone now.</i>

69
00:05:56,625 --> 00:05:59,250
<i>Our daughter is terrified.</i>
<i>She's crying her eyes out.</i>

70
00:06:00,000 --> 00:06:03,083
<i>Daddy, the police are gonna arrest you.</i>

71
00:06:05,917 --> 00:06:07,083
Hey, sweetie.

72
00:06:08,042 --> 00:06:10,125
Who's being a crybaby today?

73
00:06:11,417 --> 00:06:14,208
Those weren't police, sweetie.
Just Daddy's friends.

74
00:06:15,250 --> 00:06:16,833
They were just teasing you.

75
00:06:18,000 --> 00:06:20,500
- Do you want to go on a trip, Maysa?
<i>- Yes!</i>

76
00:06:20,583 --> 00:06:22,000
Daddy will take you on a trip.

77
00:06:22,625 --> 00:06:24,583
Let me talk to Mommy again, okay?

78
00:06:24,667 --> 00:06:28,667
[Maysa]<i> Mommy,</i>
<i>Daddy's taking us to Piggy Island!</i>

79
00:06:30,583 --> 00:06:34,000
- [music builds]
- Honey, listen to me carefully.

80
00:06:34,083 --> 00:06:35,417
[music concludes]

81
00:06:35,500 --> 00:06:36,667
[sighs]

82
00:06:37,167 --> 00:06:40,833
[cell phone buzzing, ringing]

83
00:06:45,292 --> 00:06:46,500
[car door closes]

84
00:06:47,708 --> 00:06:48,875
[Chanon] Hello.

85
00:06:52,583 --> 00:06:53,750
Okay. That's all.

86
00:06:58,333 --> 00:06:59,708
Hey, come out now!

87
00:07:07,125 --> 00:07:09,000
Hey, come out now!

88
00:07:10,250 --> 00:07:11,583
[knocking on door]

89
00:07:16,375 --> 00:07:19,375
[intense music playing]

90
00:07:22,958 --> 00:07:25,792
[engine revving]

91
00:07:25,875 --> 00:07:28,250
[man over phone] <i>I'm at Chai's house.</i>
<i>They're all gone.</i>

92
00:07:28,333 --> 00:07:29,667
<i>They've probably all fled.</i>

93
00:07:29,750 --> 00:07:32,375
Keep it guarded in case they come back,

94
00:07:33,125 --> 00:07:34,708
and track down their car, too.

95
00:07:35,208 --> 00:07:37,750
But keep it quiet. Report back to me.

96
00:07:39,208 --> 00:07:40,792
No one survived on the boat?

97
00:07:41,917 --> 00:07:44,667
All 23 workers were shot dead below deck.

98
00:07:45,833 --> 00:07:48,083
Anan really plans to silence Chai now.

99
00:07:48,875 --> 00:07:50,417
I can't lose this guy.

100
00:07:52,083 --> 00:07:53,917
We'll find Chai before they do.

101
00:07:56,417 --> 00:07:58,042
[music builds]

102
00:07:58,125 --> 00:08:00,458
- [music concludes]
- Our news team is currently stationed

103
00:08:00,542 --> 00:08:03,500
at Pol. Gen. Anan Methaneepaisal's house,

104
00:08:03,583 --> 00:08:05,917
awaiting a statement
on how his gun reportedly fell

105
00:08:06,000 --> 00:08:07,167
into the hands of a criminal,

106
00:08:07,250 --> 00:08:09,958
Mr. Chaiwut, a former police officer.

107
00:08:10,042 --> 00:08:12,833
Mr. Chaiwut was just recently
apprehended by the police

108
00:08:12,917 --> 00:08:14,625
while attempting to smuggle

109
00:08:14,708 --> 00:08:18,000
<i>a massive amount of drugs</i>
<i>through Thai waters.</i>

110
00:08:18,083 --> 00:08:20,167
<i>The police are currently investigating</i>

111
00:08:20,250 --> 00:08:22,417
<i>if anyone is behind this operation.</i>

112
00:08:22,500 --> 00:08:23,917
[electric wheelchair whirring]

113
00:08:28,083 --> 00:08:29,917
[breathes deeply]

114
00:08:32,750 --> 00:08:37,667
[electric wheelchair whirring]

115
00:08:39,875 --> 00:08:41,458
- [whirring stops]
- [wheelchair beeps]

116
00:09:01,208 --> 00:09:03,292
[Anan] Do you need something, Father?

117
00:09:03,375 --> 00:09:04,625
The reporters.

118
00:09:08,208 --> 00:09:11,667
Once everything is over,
the story will die down.

119
00:09:12,667 --> 00:09:14,333
You don't need to worry.

120
00:09:24,042 --> 00:09:26,292
Don't let everyone down.

121
00:09:26,375 --> 00:09:28,917
- [clock ticking]
- [tense music playing]

122
00:09:30,542 --> 00:09:31,625
Right.

123
00:09:35,167 --> 00:09:36,375
[wheelchair beeps]

124
00:09:44,042 --> 00:09:45,792
[cell phone buzzing]

125
00:09:53,667 --> 00:09:55,083
[Din] <i>I found him.</i>

126
00:09:55,167 --> 00:09:57,083
<i>He's hiding at the seaside safe house.</i>

127
00:09:58,583 --> 00:09:59,583
Hmm.

128
00:09:59,667 --> 00:10:01,500
[tense music continues]

129
00:10:11,125 --> 00:10:12,167
Chai!

130
00:10:13,083 --> 00:10:14,000
Chai!

131
00:10:16,167 --> 00:10:17,417
Chai!

132
00:10:19,167 --> 00:10:21,167
[sobbing]

133
00:10:22,083 --> 00:10:24,292
- [music falls]
- [clock ticking stops]

134
00:10:26,667 --> 00:10:28,333
[sobs]

135
00:10:28,417 --> 00:10:29,500
[muffled scream]

136
00:10:31,500 --> 00:10:32,542
[screams]

137
00:10:34,583 --> 00:10:38,417
[dark dramatic music playing]

138
00:10:46,875 --> 00:10:49,125
- [sobbing]
- [mutters indistinctly]

139
00:10:49,750 --> 00:10:51,000
[screams]

140
00:11:04,375 --> 00:11:07,292
[music concludes]

141
00:11:07,958 --> 00:11:11,167
[indistinct chatter]

142
00:11:13,875 --> 00:11:17,333
[soft pensive music playing]

143
00:11:47,458 --> 00:11:48,625
[music concludes]

144
00:11:48,708 --> 00:11:49,667
[door closes]

145
00:11:51,542 --> 00:11:53,708
It's not the fucking time.
You should leave.

146
00:11:54,417 --> 00:11:56,375
- [Mek] Bro…
- [Kung] I'm begging you. Just trust me.

147
00:11:56,458 --> 00:11:57,542
[door slams open]

148
00:11:58,125 --> 00:11:59,792
Do you realize what you've done?

149
00:11:59,875 --> 00:12:02,333
- Huh?!
- [soft tense music playing]

150
00:12:02,417 --> 00:12:04,625
You only thought of yourself.
Look what happened.

151
00:12:04,708 --> 00:12:08,083
Twenty-three people died
because of your selfishness!

152
00:12:09,333 --> 00:12:10,292
Actually, no.

153
00:12:11,125 --> 00:12:12,792
Twenty-four people.

154
00:12:13,292 --> 00:12:14,917
Chai is dead.

155
00:12:15,750 --> 00:12:17,333
Yeah, he's dead.

156
00:12:17,417 --> 00:12:19,333
And everything he knew died with him.

157
00:12:19,958 --> 00:12:22,708
What now? Are you going
to take responsibility for this?

158
00:12:26,375 --> 00:12:27,333
I'm sorry.

159
00:12:30,833 --> 00:12:33,083
- [door opens]
- [music concludes]

160
00:12:34,833 --> 00:12:36,000
Who are you?

161
00:12:38,917 --> 00:12:40,750
Don't you remember me?

162
00:12:45,708 --> 00:12:48,292
- Remember my daughter? Look!
- [tense music playing]

163
00:12:48,375 --> 00:12:50,833
- [Kung] Hey!
- Pui killed herself because of you!

164
00:12:50,917 --> 00:12:53,250
- [Kung] What the fuck?
- [Pui's mother] You murderers!

165
00:12:53,333 --> 00:12:55,375
- [Kung] Hey!
- Give my daughter back!

166
00:12:55,458 --> 00:12:56,417
[Kung] Hey!

167
00:12:56,500 --> 00:12:57,833
[sobs]

168
00:12:57,917 --> 00:13:00,458
- Hey!
- Give my daughter back!

169
00:13:01,542 --> 00:13:04,208
- [sobs] Give my daughter back.
- Let go.

170
00:13:04,292 --> 00:13:05,667
- [Kung arguing]
- Let her go.

171
00:13:05,750 --> 00:13:06,917
[sobs]

172
00:13:07,000 --> 00:13:09,417
- Let her go!
- Give my daughter back.

173
00:13:12,875 --> 00:13:14,833
Give my daughter back.

174
00:13:16,167 --> 00:13:18,542
Give my daughter back.

175
00:13:19,125 --> 00:13:21,667
Give my daughter back to me.

176
00:13:21,750 --> 00:13:24,750
[sorrowful music playing]

177
00:13:26,583 --> 00:13:28,958
[sobbing]

178
00:13:30,583 --> 00:13:32,083
Give my daughter back…

179
00:13:35,375 --> 00:13:37,083
[Pui's mother sobbing]

180
00:13:42,500 --> 00:13:46,542
[Pui's mother wailing]

181
00:13:50,083 --> 00:13:51,750
[sobbing]

182
00:13:55,625 --> 00:13:56,792
[door closes]

183
00:13:56,875 --> 00:13:58,667
[Pui's mother] Give my daughter back…

184
00:13:58,750 --> 00:14:05,750
PLAINTIFF IN DR. KORN CASE FOUND DEAD
SUICIDE SUSPECTED AFTER DROPPING CHARGES

185
00:14:05,833 --> 00:14:07,625
THA KOH HOSPITAL

186
00:14:07,708 --> 00:14:08,750
[music concludes]

187
00:14:28,667 --> 00:14:29,750
Does it hurt?

188
00:14:31,750 --> 00:14:33,125
[Seya] It just itches.

189
00:14:34,125 --> 00:14:35,375
Stings a little.

190
00:14:38,792 --> 00:14:40,125
[Ang] I brought you this.

191
00:14:40,708 --> 00:14:41,917
<i>Mohinga?</i>

192
00:14:43,042 --> 00:14:44,750
- [chuckles]
- [Ang] Want to eat now?

193
00:14:47,792 --> 00:14:49,250
[Seya] You know what it is?

194
00:14:50,292 --> 00:14:51,583
[Ang] Of course I do.

195
00:14:53,208 --> 00:14:55,708
[reporter over TV]
<i>…the Labor Allies Foundation secretary</i>

196
00:14:55,792 --> 00:14:57,583
<i>- who was at the arrest scene…</i>
- Thank you.

197
00:14:57,667 --> 00:15:00,000
[reporter]<i> …firmly believes</i>
<i>that the deceased migrant workers</i>

198
00:15:00,083 --> 00:15:01,792
<i>were victims of a human trafficking ring</i>

199
00:15:01,875 --> 00:15:04,125
<i>- tricked into illegal fishing.</i>
- Smell good?

200
00:15:04,208 --> 00:15:07,542
[reporter] <i>It's a problem</i>
<i>that's always been swept under the rug.</i>

201
00:15:08,250 --> 00:15:11,417
<i>Analysts predict that</i>
<i>this shooting incident on the boat</i>

202
00:15:11,500 --> 00:15:15,500
<i>will likely impact</i>
<i>the Cabinet's Fisheries Act draft,</i>

203
00:15:15,583 --> 00:15:19,208
<i>which recently passed its second reading.</i>

204
00:15:19,750 --> 00:15:20,708
Seya.

205
00:15:20,792 --> 00:15:22,167
[reporter speaking indistinctly]

206
00:15:22,250 --> 00:15:23,250
[Seya sniffs]

207
00:15:25,875 --> 00:15:28,125
What if we can't find Nay Oo?

208
00:15:36,500 --> 00:15:38,583
I'll keep looking until I do.

209
00:15:42,458 --> 00:15:43,500
[sniffles]

210
00:15:45,833 --> 00:15:47,458
[Seya] Because I have no one left, either.

211
00:15:47,542 --> 00:15:48,583
[sobs softly]

212
00:15:49,917 --> 00:15:50,875
[sniffles]

213
00:15:54,333 --> 00:15:55,583
What's wrong?

214
00:15:59,542 --> 00:16:00,750
[sobs]

215
00:16:00,833 --> 00:16:02,458
[Seya] What's wrong?

216
00:16:03,792 --> 00:16:05,000
I'm sorry.

217
00:16:06,750 --> 00:16:08,333
I'm really sorry.

218
00:16:11,708 --> 00:16:13,500
The night Nee An died…

219
00:16:15,083 --> 00:16:16,542
I was on the boat, too.

220
00:16:18,417 --> 00:16:20,542
But I couldn't do anything to help.

221
00:16:22,167 --> 00:16:24,917
I gave her CPR, but it was too late--

222
00:16:25,000 --> 00:16:28,000
Then they threw her body in the water?

223
00:16:32,583 --> 00:16:36,333
Nay Oo told me what they did to Nee An.

224
00:16:38,833 --> 00:16:41,208
She said you tried to help.

225
00:16:43,667 --> 00:16:44,917
But you couldn't.

226
00:16:45,000 --> 00:16:46,250
[Ang sobbing]

227
00:16:46,917 --> 00:16:48,792
[Seya] Nay Oo remembered your name.

228
00:16:51,750 --> 00:16:54,542
I know it wasn't your fault.

229
00:16:58,583 --> 00:17:00,833
We're not angry with you.

230
00:17:01,792 --> 00:17:04,208
[tender music playing]

231
00:17:06,083 --> 00:17:08,958
[sobs, sniffles]

232
00:17:13,042 --> 00:17:15,625
If I had told the truth from day one,

233
00:17:16,917 --> 00:17:19,833
it wouldn't… we wouldn't be here today.

234
00:17:25,083 --> 00:17:27,625
Do you think the truth can help us?

235
00:17:28,667 --> 00:17:31,125
[dark pensive music playing]

236
00:17:33,292 --> 00:17:34,458
[Seya] Hmm?

237
00:17:39,958 --> 00:17:42,792
- [birds chirping]
- [dark pensive music conitnues]

238
00:17:52,833 --> 00:17:55,833
[Rit] Oh, why'd you set out two plates?

239
00:17:56,333 --> 00:17:58,583
Mek has been here since dawn.

240
00:18:08,542 --> 00:18:11,167
[Rit] Were you so stressed
that you came back home?

241
00:18:14,292 --> 00:18:15,667
It's about the case, right?

242
00:18:16,375 --> 00:18:19,250
- [music fades]
- Here, stay and eat with me first.

243
00:18:19,333 --> 00:18:20,833
Noi already cooked something.

244
00:18:21,667 --> 00:18:23,292
[Mek] It's fine. I'm not hungry.

245
00:18:23,875 --> 00:18:26,500
They changed the judge for your case.

246
00:18:31,083 --> 00:18:34,750
Someone filed a complaint about the delay,

247
00:18:34,833 --> 00:18:36,917
because Jittri stalled for time.

248
00:18:38,000 --> 00:18:40,750
So the chief gave it to Padung instead.

249
00:18:43,542 --> 00:18:46,042
Telling me insider news before the trial?

250
00:18:46,833 --> 00:18:48,458
That's not like you, Dad.

251
00:18:50,917 --> 00:18:53,667
You know what it means
that Padung is the judge, right?

252
00:18:56,708 --> 00:18:58,875
I'll lose the case and go to prison.

253
00:18:58,958 --> 00:19:01,583
Everyone knows you two are locking horns.

254
00:19:04,125 --> 00:19:06,958
Tell Jittri to prepare a good defense.

255
00:19:09,750 --> 00:19:12,708
Judges must remain impartial.

256
00:19:13,583 --> 00:19:16,417
You preached that your whole life.
Why forget it now?

257
00:19:17,917 --> 00:19:18,917
[Rit sighs]

258
00:19:27,042 --> 00:19:28,958
Will you really never forgive me?

259
00:19:29,042 --> 00:19:30,042
[loud thud]

260
00:19:31,042 --> 00:19:32,083
For what, Dad?

261
00:19:32,958 --> 00:19:33,875
Huh, Dad?

262
00:19:34,375 --> 00:19:37,042
For clinging to your principles
until Mom died?

263
00:19:37,792 --> 00:19:41,375
Or that even today,
you still don't admit it was your fault?

264
00:19:42,042 --> 00:19:43,667
What exactly should I forgive you for?

265
00:19:50,792 --> 00:19:54,000
What would you do if you were in my shoes?

266
00:19:56,458 --> 00:19:59,250
That cop gunned down
a whole innocent family, Mek.

267
00:19:59,958 --> 00:20:01,542
Did Mom deserve to die?

268
00:20:02,417 --> 00:20:03,708
Huh, Dad?

269
00:20:03,792 --> 00:20:07,333
What about me? I was stuck in that car.

270
00:20:07,417 --> 00:20:09,542
I saw Mom get shot right in front of me.

271
00:20:10,917 --> 00:20:12,917
Did I deserve to witness that?

272
00:20:14,958 --> 00:20:18,125
In her last moments,
Mom still believed you'd change your mind.

273
00:20:19,750 --> 00:20:21,208
[breathes shakily]

274
00:20:21,292 --> 00:20:24,875
You help everyone.
You're so fucking impartial.

275
00:20:26,875 --> 00:20:28,500
But you betrayed us.

276
00:20:36,167 --> 00:20:38,792
So you want me to judge based on orders…

277
00:20:40,917 --> 00:20:43,208
just like what Padung will do to you?

278
00:20:43,958 --> 00:20:46,667
[pensive music playing]

279
00:20:58,333 --> 00:21:00,917
[pensive music continues]

280
00:21:16,000 --> 00:21:19,417
MS. PRAPASSORN BOONKAMHOM

281
00:21:28,375 --> 00:21:30,542
- [leaves rustling]
- [music concludes]

282
00:21:35,625 --> 00:21:39,208
[bell tolling in distance]

283
00:21:52,125 --> 00:21:53,750
[Mek] I didn't think you'd come.

284
00:21:55,708 --> 00:21:56,750
Why?

285
00:21:56,833 --> 00:21:59,125
Do I seem that cruel to you?

286
00:21:59,208 --> 00:22:01,167
[birds chirping]

287
00:22:06,583 --> 00:22:08,875
After you let her mom slap you like that,

288
00:22:08,958 --> 00:22:10,750
did that make you feel better?

289
00:22:13,458 --> 00:22:14,458
No.

290
00:22:15,750 --> 00:22:17,667
But at least her mother feels like

291
00:22:17,750 --> 00:22:20,625
she's done something
to get justice for her kid.

292
00:22:27,292 --> 00:22:29,875
Justice for the dead?

293
00:22:40,500 --> 00:22:41,833
Is it something important?

294
00:22:45,000 --> 00:22:46,042
It's not.

295
00:22:48,125 --> 00:22:49,958
The person who gave it to me is.

296
00:22:56,500 --> 00:22:57,708
Muleng.

297
00:22:59,542 --> 00:23:00,875
That's my name.

298
00:23:02,958 --> 00:23:04,708
The name my parents gave me.

299
00:23:05,875 --> 00:23:07,500
When you lived in Tak?

300
00:23:11,458 --> 00:23:12,792
Ban Mae Tawo,

301
00:23:13,625 --> 00:23:15,500
a tiny village by the Moei River.

302
00:23:17,083 --> 00:23:19,542
Just a short trip across to Myanmar.

303
00:23:21,458 --> 00:23:23,208
My dad was a ferryman.

304
00:23:24,542 --> 00:23:25,708
Loved the casino too.

305
00:23:27,833 --> 00:23:30,250
He gave me this chip as a lucky charm.

306
00:23:31,333 --> 00:23:32,708
But the day I got it,

307
00:23:33,667 --> 00:23:35,250
everything started going downhill.

308
00:23:35,333 --> 00:23:37,167
[soft pensive music playing]

309
00:23:37,250 --> 00:23:39,083
[boat engine rumbling]

310
00:23:45,833 --> 00:23:47,333
[in Shan] Muleng.

311
00:23:48,792 --> 00:23:52,167
Keep this. When you're older,
I'll teach you how to play.

312
00:23:56,625 --> 00:23:58,125
Okay!

313
00:24:03,375 --> 00:24:05,250
[Jittri in Thai]<i> My dad was too kind.</i>

314
00:24:07,208 --> 00:24:10,208
<i>He'd help ferry workers from Myanmar.</i>

315
00:24:19,917 --> 00:24:21,292
[Anan] Are you Mr. Jai?

316
00:24:22,333 --> 00:24:25,042
[Jittri] <i>Anan was the deputy chief</i>
<i>in Mae Moei then.</i>

317
00:24:25,125 --> 00:24:26,833
[foreboding music playing]

318
00:24:26,917 --> 00:24:29,292
[Jittri] <i>He probably thought</i>
<i>Dad was in his way.</i>

319
00:24:30,000 --> 00:24:33,000
[Chai] Ouch! Let go, you little bitch!

320
00:24:33,667 --> 00:24:35,542
[Jittri] <i>He was just a simple ferryman,</i>

321
00:24:36,417 --> 00:24:38,000
<i>but he was framed for human trafficking.</i>

322
00:24:38,083 --> 00:24:39,167
Daddy!

323
00:24:40,458 --> 00:24:42,833
[Kwan] How can you frame innocent people?
Where is he?

324
00:24:42,917 --> 00:24:44,292
Answer me! Where is he?

325
00:24:44,375 --> 00:24:46,708
[Jittri] <i>Mom and I went to the station.</i>

326
00:24:46,792 --> 00:24:49,375
<i>They blatantly lied that Dad had run away.</i>

327
00:24:50,625 --> 00:24:52,625
<i>So he became a fugitive.</i>

328
00:24:53,458 --> 00:24:55,083
<i>My mom never believed it.</i>

329
00:24:55,167 --> 00:24:56,375
Where did you take him?

330
00:24:56,458 --> 00:24:57,583
[Jittri] <i>She knew him well.</i>

331
00:24:57,667 --> 00:24:59,625
[Kwan] He's my husband! He's my family!

332
00:25:00,417 --> 00:25:02,875
- [somber music playing]
- [Jittri] <i>We searched for him everywhere.</i>

333
00:25:02,958 --> 00:25:05,833
<i>We appealed, but no one listened.</i>

334
00:25:05,917 --> 00:25:07,500
- Excuse me.
- Get up, ma'am.

335
00:25:07,583 --> 00:25:09,083
- [Kwan] I have proof!
- Get up!

336
00:25:09,167 --> 00:25:12,292
- [Kwan] I have proof!
- [officer] Ma'am, please don't.

337
00:25:12,375 --> 00:25:14,208
[muffled shouting]

338
00:25:14,292 --> 00:25:16,375
You don't help because you're one of them!

339
00:25:17,875 --> 00:25:21,625
[Jittri] <i>The more they ignored us,</i>
<i>the more Mom believed he had been killed.</i>

340
00:25:23,750 --> 00:25:25,875
<i>Eventually, no one wanted</i>
<i>to deal with her.</i>

341
00:25:29,833 --> 00:25:31,208
In the end…

342
00:25:33,333 --> 00:25:34,917
someone found her body.

343
00:25:35,000 --> 00:25:36,542
- [waves crashing]
- [music concludes]

344
00:25:36,625 --> 00:25:38,417
She drowned at the pier,

345
00:25:39,708 --> 00:25:41,542
right where my dad worked every day.

346
00:25:44,792 --> 00:25:46,750
Everyone said my mom killed herself.

347
00:25:47,708 --> 00:25:48,625
[scoffs softly]

348
00:25:49,125 --> 00:25:50,792
A woman like her, killing herself?

349
00:25:50,875 --> 00:25:52,542
[soft tense music playing]

350
00:25:52,625 --> 00:25:54,083
I never believed that.

351
00:25:57,208 --> 00:25:59,708
Even if the statute
of limitations on my dad's case is up,

352
00:25:59,792 --> 00:26:01,042
and I can't make him pay,

353
00:26:02,250 --> 00:26:03,500
all I can do is hope…

354
00:26:06,375 --> 00:26:07,958
for just one chance.

355
00:26:09,958 --> 00:26:11,250
Just one.

356
00:26:13,458 --> 00:26:15,750
Then I'll take all the sick shit he did

357
00:26:16,542 --> 00:26:17,917
and use it to destroy him.

358
00:26:25,667 --> 00:26:27,667
My case is that chance, isn't it?

359
00:26:32,542 --> 00:26:34,542
It's not that I don't want to help you.

360
00:26:36,917 --> 00:26:38,417
I see your stubbornness.

361
00:26:38,500 --> 00:26:39,833
How you'd do anything

362
00:26:39,917 --> 00:26:42,083
to prove you're not who they say you are.

363
00:26:44,958 --> 00:26:46,500
My mom was like that too.

364
00:26:50,375 --> 00:26:52,500
She swore up and down he was innocent…

365
00:26:54,500 --> 00:26:56,667
even when no one believed her.

366
00:27:03,250 --> 00:27:06,583
Do you ever think
you could've done more?

367
00:27:08,292 --> 00:27:09,917
[Jittri] To protect my parents?

368
00:27:14,333 --> 00:27:16,917
Do you? With your mom?

369
00:27:19,958 --> 00:27:21,333
Every single day.

370
00:27:32,833 --> 00:27:35,250
[music fades]

371
00:27:38,042 --> 00:27:39,750
Guess we're on the same team then.

372
00:27:43,167 --> 00:27:44,208
What team?

373
00:27:45,042 --> 00:27:46,208
Anan's victims team?

374
00:27:46,750 --> 00:27:48,125
[soft pensive music playing]

375
00:27:48,208 --> 00:27:50,458
Look, I don't even like you that much.

376
00:27:50,542 --> 00:27:51,958
You play too many tricks.

377
00:27:52,042 --> 00:27:53,333
I can never read you

378
00:27:53,417 --> 00:27:55,458
and you spin everything in your favor.

379
00:27:55,542 --> 00:27:58,458
- And you probably think I'm just--
- [Jittri] Reckless.

380
00:27:58,542 --> 00:28:01,375
Stubborn, and you never listen to anyone.

381
00:28:06,167 --> 00:28:08,333
We don't have to like each other.

382
00:28:09,375 --> 00:28:11,208
We just need to share the same goal.

383
00:28:19,667 --> 00:28:22,583
- Is that really necessary?
- Come on.

384
00:28:27,542 --> 00:28:29,125
You've watched too many movies.

385
00:28:30,750 --> 00:28:32,458
[Jittri chuckles softly]

386
00:28:44,458 --> 00:28:45,750
Right this way, please.

387
00:28:46,333 --> 00:28:48,833
- [Padung in English] Hi, Andy.
- Hi, Padung.

388
00:28:48,917 --> 00:28:51,208
Sorry to keep you waiting.

389
00:28:51,958 --> 00:28:54,875
[in Thai] This is Andy,
Mr. Zhou Feng's assistant.

390
00:28:54,958 --> 00:28:57,833
[in English] Mr. Andy, here is my friend.

391
00:28:58,292 --> 00:29:00,375
Please meet Mr. Rit.

392
00:29:00,500 --> 00:29:02,625
[soft tense music playing]

393
00:29:02,708 --> 00:29:05,875
[Padung] He's going to help us
with the factory fire case.

394
00:29:08,458 --> 00:29:10,625
[sirens blaring in the distance]

395
00:29:11,250 --> 00:29:17,917
PLAINTIFF WITNESS EXAMINATION:
GOLF COURSE CASE

396
00:29:29,292 --> 00:29:31,542
[soft tense music continues]

397
00:29:40,875 --> 00:29:42,375
[cell phone buzzing]

398
00:29:46,208 --> 00:29:50,042
ANG: DON'T WORRY.
THE TRUTH WILL PROTECT US.

399
00:29:52,333 --> 00:29:54,958
[music fades]

400
00:29:56,833 --> 00:30:02,667
[camera shutters clicking]

401
00:30:03,250 --> 00:30:05,875
[thrilling music playing]

402
00:30:06,542 --> 00:30:08,792
[Nemo] Excuse me!
Make way for the lawyer, please.

403
00:30:08,875 --> 00:30:11,542
[reporter 1] Attorney,
what are your thoughts on today's hearing?

404
00:30:11,625 --> 00:30:13,958
I hear the court won't allow
the second postponement.

405
00:30:14,042 --> 00:30:16,500
Are you worried
you won't get a fair trial?

406
00:30:16,583 --> 00:30:17,750
[reporter 2] Comment, please.

407
00:30:17,833 --> 00:30:19,042
[Padung] Really?

408
00:30:20,375 --> 00:30:22,708
No, I've been in meetings all morning.

409
00:30:22,792 --> 00:30:23,958
Yeah.

410
00:30:24,042 --> 00:30:25,042
Right.

411
00:30:25,750 --> 00:30:29,542
I'm really craving some red duck curry

412
00:30:29,625 --> 00:30:31,000
from the usual place.

413
00:30:33,042 --> 00:30:34,167
Two orders.

414
00:30:34,250 --> 00:30:36,125
Don't forget the cockles!

415
00:30:37,167 --> 00:30:38,208
[in English] Okay, okay.

416
00:30:38,292 --> 00:30:40,375
[in Thai] I've gotta get to work now.

417
00:30:40,458 --> 00:30:42,042
See you this evening, sweetie.

418
00:30:42,833 --> 00:30:44,542
Yeah, bye now.

419
00:30:46,208 --> 00:30:47,750
[music rises]

420
00:30:49,625 --> 00:30:51,625
[music concludes]

421
00:30:53,500 --> 00:30:55,375
[chairs scraping]

422
00:31:08,125 --> 00:31:11,292
Case O.927/2568.

423
00:31:12,542 --> 00:31:14,667
Both the plaintiff and defense
are present.

424
00:31:15,500 --> 00:31:16,792
You may begin.

425
00:31:18,583 --> 00:31:21,417
The prosecution moves to remove
Mr. Sorn Saengruengnop

426
00:31:21,500 --> 00:31:22,750
from our witness list

427
00:31:22,833 --> 00:31:27,042
as he's involved with the defendant
in the ordination shooting case.

428
00:31:27,750 --> 00:31:29,875
We're afraid
they might collude outside of court.

429
00:31:29,958 --> 00:31:31,625
The court grants the removal.

430
00:31:32,708 --> 00:31:34,458
I assume the defense has no objections.

431
00:31:34,542 --> 00:31:36,458
It does seem inappropriate.

432
00:31:36,542 --> 00:31:38,458
No objections, Your Honor. Understood.

433
00:31:40,083 --> 00:31:42,833
[prosecutor] I'd like to call
the forensic expert.

434
00:31:42,917 --> 00:31:44,500
[approaching footsteps]

435
00:31:48,000 --> 00:31:50,833
[forensic expert] Based on
the fingerprints found on the golf club,

436
00:31:50,917 --> 00:31:55,208
aside from the victim's,
only the defendant's prints were found.

437
00:31:55,292 --> 00:31:59,250
We conclude the killer used the club
to strike the victim's head

438
00:32:00,083 --> 00:32:01,833
by gripping the middle of the handle,

439
00:32:01,917 --> 00:32:04,083
as shown by the prints on the screen.

440
00:32:04,167 --> 00:32:07,375
The skull was struck repeatedly,
about four to five times.

441
00:32:07,458 --> 00:32:08,625
[echoing scream]

442
00:32:09,167 --> 00:32:12,083
[forensic expert] During the first strike,
blood wouldn't splatter yet.

443
00:32:12,167 --> 00:32:14,458
It would only cause subcutaneous bruising.

444
00:32:14,542 --> 00:32:18,125
The second strike
would fracture the skull.

445
00:32:19,167 --> 00:32:21,250
Once the wound opened, blood splattered.

446
00:32:25,458 --> 00:32:27,167
[prosecutor] No further questions.

447
00:32:29,667 --> 00:32:31,583
The defense may cross-examine.

448
00:32:36,000 --> 00:32:37,833
Based on document WJ.12,

449
00:32:38,542 --> 00:32:40,542
could you summarize it simply for us?

450
00:32:40,625 --> 00:32:44,250
What caused the bloodstains
on the shoulder and the hem?

451
00:32:45,833 --> 00:32:47,458
The bloodstain on the shoulder

452
00:32:47,542 --> 00:32:51,125
likely came from raising the club
off the victim's head to strike again.

453
00:32:51,625 --> 00:32:53,500
As for the stain on the hem,

454
00:32:53,583 --> 00:32:56,667
it likely transferred from the floor
after the victim's death.

455
00:32:58,417 --> 00:33:01,333
In that case, I'd like to test
the witness's claim.

456
00:33:02,000 --> 00:33:05,875
I already filed a motion
to bring in equipment.

457
00:33:05,958 --> 00:33:07,625
I hope there are no objections,
Your Honor.

458
00:33:07,708 --> 00:33:10,875
[funky intriguing music playing]

459
00:33:11,500 --> 00:33:14,500
[equipment rattling]

460
00:33:26,208 --> 00:33:28,125
This is a blood splatter dummy.

461
00:33:28,208 --> 00:33:30,208
It simulates blunt force trauma.

462
00:33:30,292 --> 00:33:33,083
We'll conduct a test
as close to reality as possible.

463
00:33:33,667 --> 00:33:35,750
I request permission to remove my robe.

464
00:33:37,250 --> 00:33:40,000
Just the facts. Skip the theatrics.

465
00:33:42,417 --> 00:33:43,958
So it won't cut into lunch break.

466
00:33:49,083 --> 00:33:50,125
[music concludes]

467
00:33:52,083 --> 00:33:54,083
[fast daring music playing]

468
00:33:54,833 --> 00:33:56,583
One strike really draws no blood.

469
00:34:01,375 --> 00:34:03,708
[squelching thuds]

470
00:34:06,083 --> 00:34:08,125
Your Honor, this is excessive!

471
00:34:08,208 --> 00:34:10,750
This is excessive. That's enough.

472
00:34:13,375 --> 00:34:16,125
It's a realistic simulation
so you get the full picture.

473
00:34:18,542 --> 00:34:20,583
- [screams]
- What are you doing?

474
00:34:20,667 --> 00:34:23,125
- [music falls]
- Just asking how the killer held the club.

475
00:34:23,208 --> 00:34:24,250
Like this?

476
00:34:24,333 --> 00:34:25,750
- Or like this?
- Stop!

477
00:34:26,417 --> 00:34:28,292
- Officer, confiscate the club.
- [officer] Yes.

478
00:34:28,375 --> 00:34:29,708
Hold on, ma'am.

479
00:34:29,792 --> 00:34:31,167
- Stop.
- [Jittri grunts]

480
00:34:32,875 --> 00:34:34,083
[Padung] Stop!

481
00:34:34,750 --> 00:34:38,208
The defense's cross-examination
ends right here.

482
00:34:38,292 --> 00:34:39,667
- [music fades]
- Understood.

483
00:34:40,208 --> 00:34:43,208
Because if the officer's shirt
gets splashed with red liquid like this,

484
00:34:43,292 --> 00:34:45,000
I don't need to ask anything else.

485
00:34:46,125 --> 00:34:48,042
Do you see? [pants]

486
00:34:48,125 --> 00:34:51,708
The blood splatter wasn't caused
solely by the impact of the strikes.

487
00:34:51,792 --> 00:34:55,125
It could have come from struggling
over the club to save the victim.

488
00:34:55,917 --> 00:34:57,750
[pants]

489
00:34:57,833 --> 00:34:59,083
No further questions.

490
00:35:02,708 --> 00:35:05,042
PUBLIC GALLERY

491
00:35:09,417 --> 00:35:12,042
Prosecution, no more witnesses?

492
00:35:14,000 --> 00:35:15,833
I will now adjourn this hearing.

493
00:35:15,917 --> 00:35:17,083
[Jittri] Hold on, Your Honor.

494
00:35:17,167 --> 00:35:20,875
The defense requests the admission
of additional evidence.

495
00:35:20,958 --> 00:35:23,750
We have a witness
who can confirm the presence

496
00:35:23,833 --> 00:35:25,500
of a third party at the scene.

497
00:35:25,583 --> 00:35:28,208
And a doctor who can certify
the defendant's injuries.

498
00:35:28,833 --> 00:35:32,042
Do you not know it's against protocol
to add new witnesses, Counsel?

499
00:35:32,125 --> 00:35:35,208
But this crucial information
will impact the case, Your Honor.

500
00:35:36,000 --> 00:35:38,583
I urge you to consider it thoroughly.

501
00:35:39,667 --> 00:35:40,542
Denied.

502
00:35:41,417 --> 00:35:43,333
Before you dismiss anything,

503
00:35:43,417 --> 00:35:45,542
why don't you read the document first?

504
00:35:45,625 --> 00:35:47,333
Watch your tone, Counsel.

505
00:35:47,875 --> 00:35:49,208
I'll hold you in contempt.

506
00:35:49,958 --> 00:35:51,333
I have the right to refuse it.

507
00:35:52,417 --> 00:35:54,542
I just want you to consider it first.

508
00:35:55,292 --> 00:35:57,375
Because if you dismiss it outright,

509
00:35:57,917 --> 00:36:00,000
I'm afraid you might be investigated.

510
00:36:11,250 --> 00:36:12,833
MOTION FOR ADDITIONAL WITNESSES

511
00:36:12,917 --> 00:36:14,792
MOTION TO RECUSE THE JUDGE

512
00:36:14,875 --> 00:36:16,208
[Padung] What is this?

513
00:36:16,292 --> 00:36:18,583
- [tense music playing]
- A motion to recuse the judge?

514
00:36:18,667 --> 00:36:21,583
Oh my! Did I grab the wrong document?

515
00:36:22,208 --> 00:36:26,375
I was preparing to file a motion
because my investigation found that

516
00:36:26,458 --> 00:36:29,208
you and Mr. Anan have a good history.

517
00:36:29,292 --> 00:36:32,292
Since you attended the same college.

518
00:36:33,542 --> 00:36:36,167
Attending the same college
isn't against the rules.

519
00:36:36,250 --> 00:36:38,292
That college has thousands of students.

520
00:36:38,917 --> 00:36:40,208
Going to the same college

521
00:36:40,292 --> 00:36:42,625
doesn't mean we actually know each other.

522
00:36:43,625 --> 00:36:47,083
So you're officially objecting
to my lawsuit.

523
00:36:49,083 --> 00:36:54,500
It's clear you have a strong bias
in this case.

524
00:36:56,542 --> 00:36:57,792
I'm not biased.

525
00:36:58,292 --> 00:36:59,833
Sue me if you want.

526
00:37:00,625 --> 00:37:03,375
The court won't even consider this.

527
00:37:03,458 --> 00:37:05,833
If you're truly not biased,

528
00:37:05,917 --> 00:37:09,833
then please accept
this additional evidence,

529
00:37:10,542 --> 00:37:15,417
so I can be certain
this case will be judged impartially.

530
00:37:16,625 --> 00:37:18,583
[music rises]

531
00:37:39,375 --> 00:37:42,292
20 YEARS OF RUAM THAI PARTY
STEPPING INTO THE FUTURE

532
00:37:42,375 --> 00:37:44,458
[man] Congratulations, Dr. Atch.

533
00:37:45,000 --> 00:37:47,042
[woman] Let me know if you need anything.

534
00:37:47,125 --> 00:37:49,292
I'm fully committed to helping.

535
00:37:49,375 --> 00:37:51,292
- Understood?
- Ang, honey.

536
00:37:53,500 --> 00:37:55,792
- Hello.
- [woman] Hello.

537
00:37:55,875 --> 00:37:58,958
Ang, this is Ms. Nongnuch,
CEO of Bay Energy.

538
00:37:59,042 --> 00:38:03,042
And this is Mr. Songpol,
the tycoon of the Songpol Group,

539
00:38:03,125 --> 00:38:05,542
the largest processed seafood exporter.

540
00:38:06,167 --> 00:38:08,667
They have always supported our party.

541
00:38:09,375 --> 00:38:12,292
And they really admire your idea
to rebrand the party.

542
00:38:13,292 --> 00:38:15,500
She is our main driving force.

543
00:38:15,583 --> 00:38:16,667
[Songpol] Your mom mentioned

544
00:38:16,750 --> 00:38:20,625
you're pushing
the new Fisheries Act, right?

545
00:38:20,708 --> 00:38:22,333
- [Atchara] Yes, she's the one.
- I didn't--

546
00:38:22,417 --> 00:38:23,750
She deals with the NGOs.

547
00:38:23,833 --> 00:38:26,250
Otherwise, we'd never reach an agreement.

548
00:38:26,333 --> 00:38:27,333
[soft tense music playing]

549
00:38:27,417 --> 00:38:31,167
Thank you so much.
The old laws are too strict.

550
00:38:31,250 --> 00:38:34,542
It's so hard
for businessmen like us to operate.

551
00:38:34,625 --> 00:38:37,750
Those NGOs are so stubborn
and unreasonable.

552
00:38:38,375 --> 00:38:42,083
They attack the business sector
over everything,

553
00:38:42,167 --> 00:38:45,125
making us look like villains all the time.

554
00:38:45,208 --> 00:38:47,750
Exactly. I've always taught her

555
00:38:47,833 --> 00:38:50,083
that if we believe in what we do,

556
00:38:50,167 --> 00:38:53,542
we must stand firm.
People will understand someday.

557
00:38:53,625 --> 00:38:57,292
- [Nongnuch] We're counting on you.
- [Songpol] You have my full support.

558
00:38:57,375 --> 00:38:59,000
- Excuse me.
- [Nongnuch] Oh.

559
00:39:01,000 --> 00:39:04,750
She's probably a bit nervous
since she has to speak soon.

560
00:39:04,833 --> 00:39:06,542
[presenter]
To move the country forward,

561
00:39:06,625 --> 00:39:09,750
we must always stand united
to build a stable nation.

562
00:39:09,833 --> 00:39:11,542
[Ang] This is
the latest presentation file.

563
00:39:11,625 --> 00:39:12,708
Please update it.

564
00:39:12,792 --> 00:39:15,625
We decided to step into a new era…

565
00:39:15,708 --> 00:39:17,833
How are you doing, sweetie? Nervous?

566
00:39:18,625 --> 00:39:20,125
Have you memorized the script?

567
00:39:23,167 --> 00:39:27,333
I know there's a lot you dislike
and want to change.

568
00:39:28,125 --> 00:39:31,708
But to change anything,
we need power first.

569
00:39:32,417 --> 00:39:34,708
Our party is your power.

570
00:39:35,292 --> 00:39:36,625
Make sure you succeed.

571
00:39:38,542 --> 00:39:40,333
And when that time comes,

572
00:39:40,417 --> 00:39:42,042
whatever you want to change,

573
00:39:42,542 --> 00:39:44,417
the chance will be yours.

574
00:39:47,125 --> 00:39:48,958
When you first entered politics,

575
00:39:49,750 --> 00:39:51,875
what did you want to do first?

576
00:39:52,417 --> 00:39:56,042
You already know it, honey.
Don't you remember?

577
00:39:57,167 --> 00:39:58,750
The provincial VIPs.

578
00:39:58,833 --> 00:40:02,125
I always hated the double standards
at the hospital.

579
00:40:02,208 --> 00:40:04,542
They always treated the VIPs first.

580
00:40:05,042 --> 00:40:07,500
The rich and the poor
deserve equal rights.

581
00:40:08,125 --> 00:40:11,500
Remember? I tackled that issue first.

582
00:40:11,583 --> 00:40:13,875
Inequality in hospitals.

583
00:40:15,917 --> 00:40:18,708
Should we use this campaign
for our next election?

584
00:40:20,542 --> 00:40:23,792
It perfectly fits your image
as the new generation.

585
00:40:25,917 --> 00:40:27,625
All people are equal.

586
00:40:29,042 --> 00:40:30,625
Sounds good? What do you think?

587
00:40:36,458 --> 00:40:38,542
You're probably tired of listening to me.

588
00:40:39,667 --> 00:40:41,833
But I'm so proud of you.

589
00:40:43,042 --> 00:40:46,792
[presenter] Next, please welcome
Ms. Angsumalin Thumnart,

590
00:40:46,875 --> 00:40:48,667
- head of the working committee…
- Mom.

591
00:40:48,750 --> 00:40:50,583
[presenter] …for the Ruam Thai Party
rebranding.

592
00:40:50,667 --> 00:40:53,083
She is the legacy and the new blood
of the Ruam Thai Party…

593
00:40:53,167 --> 00:40:55,667
- Thanks for your trust.
- …who will deliver the opening speech.

594
00:40:55,750 --> 00:40:58,250
- Please give her a round of applause.
- Can I trust you?

595
00:40:58,333 --> 00:41:00,917
- [crowd applauding]
- Don't ruin my reputation, okay?

596
00:41:03,917 --> 00:41:07,208
[uplifting music playing over speakers]

597
00:41:09,125 --> 00:41:11,917
- [crowd applauding]
- [camera shutters clicking]

598
00:41:18,083 --> 00:41:20,083
[breathes deeply]

599
00:41:20,167 --> 00:41:21,458
[music concludes]

600
00:41:21,542 --> 00:41:23,042
Good afternoon, everyone.

601
00:41:23,750 --> 00:41:25,958
Thank you for joining us today.

602
00:41:28,042 --> 00:41:29,500
As you all know,

603
00:41:30,000 --> 00:41:32,750
the Ruam Thai Party
has reached its 20th year,

604
00:41:33,625 --> 00:41:36,958
which is more than half my lifetime.

605
00:41:38,250 --> 00:41:39,375
When I was little,

606
00:41:40,167 --> 00:41:42,542
I spent enough time at my mom's hospital

607
00:41:42,625 --> 00:41:44,750
that it became my second home.

608
00:41:45,458 --> 00:41:47,250
There were only a few doctors,

609
00:41:47,917 --> 00:41:51,375
so she worked every day without a day off.

610
00:41:54,167 --> 00:41:55,500
But one day,

611
00:41:56,333 --> 00:42:00,708
she told me she'd stop treating patients.

612
00:42:04,375 --> 00:42:07,667
I later learned she was forced to resign

613
00:42:08,417 --> 00:42:12,875
for treating hill tribe patients
before the provincial VIPs.

614
00:42:14,833 --> 00:42:17,000
As a kid, I was angry at her.

615
00:42:19,958 --> 00:42:21,958
But when I went back to that hospital,

616
00:42:23,750 --> 00:42:27,667
I could feel that the other doctors
looked at her differently.

617
00:42:28,917 --> 00:42:31,667
- [camera shutter clicks]
- Like she wasn't just a doctor…

618
00:42:32,625 --> 00:42:35,958
but she was a hero
who acted as their voice.

619
00:42:37,417 --> 00:42:40,500
And they no longer saw me
as a doctor's daughter,

620
00:42:41,500 --> 00:42:43,583
but as the daughter of their hero.

621
00:42:47,875 --> 00:42:49,875
I am incredibly proud of my mother.

622
00:42:51,375 --> 00:42:54,542
Because from that day until now…

623
00:42:56,542 --> 00:42:58,583
she has remained the same person…

624
00:43:00,750 --> 00:43:04,125
who taught me to see people as equals,

625
00:43:05,167 --> 00:43:11,833
be they a tycoon, a civil servant,
a police officer, a soldier…

626
00:43:14,542 --> 00:43:16,958
or a Burmese waitress

627
00:43:17,042 --> 00:43:18,042
named Nee An.

628
00:43:18,125 --> 00:43:19,083
[tense music playing]

629
00:43:19,167 --> 00:43:20,625
MYSTERY CORPSE IN CHAO PHRAYA RIVER

630
00:43:20,708 --> 00:43:23,792
Nee An was a waitress at a gathering
for the Ruam Thai Party,

631
00:43:24,417 --> 00:43:27,583
held on the boat belonging to
Police General Anan Methaneepaisal.

632
00:43:27,667 --> 00:43:28,625
[crowd murmuring]

633
00:43:28,708 --> 00:43:31,167
[Ang] She died after being forced to drink

634
00:43:31,250 --> 00:43:32,750
by Minister Suwat,

635
00:43:33,667 --> 00:43:35,375
which led to acute heart failure.

636
00:43:35,458 --> 00:43:37,833
Her body was then dumped in the river

637
00:43:38,458 --> 00:43:40,583
to protect the guests on the boat.

638
00:43:40,667 --> 00:43:43,667
I am deeply ashamed
to have been a part of

639
00:43:43,750 --> 00:43:45,625
such a despicable act.

640
00:43:46,375 --> 00:43:49,792
Therefore, I announce my resignation
from the Ruam Thai Party.

641
00:43:49,875 --> 00:43:52,125
- And I demand that…
- [microphone feedback whines]

642
00:43:52,208 --> 00:43:54,083
- [crowd clamoring]
- …that everyone involved

643
00:43:54,167 --> 00:43:56,792
take responsibility for this incident.

644
00:43:56,875 --> 00:43:58,458
- [staff member] Ms. Ang.
- [music rises]

645
00:43:58,542 --> 00:43:59,917
[music concludes]

646
00:44:00,000 --> 00:44:02,500
[dark intriguing music playing]

647
00:45:20,083 --> 00:45:24,000
[dark tense music playing]

648
00:46:21,208 --> 00:46:22,792
[music concludes]
